sentences: Blanche Hermine Barbot (December 28, 1842 - December 17, 1919) was a Belgian-American musical director and pianist.

At the age of seven, she was already so accomplished a pianist that Marie Pleyel complimented Barbot most warmly on her playing and predicted for her a brilliant future upon the concert stage, for which her father destined her.
Her first appearance in concert was in the Theatre Italien-Francais, in Brussels, in February, 1851.
The family removed to New York City in the spring of 1852 where several concerts were given by the father and daughter.

After her father fell victim to yellow fever in the epidemic of 1856, leaving his family in such strained circumstances that all thought of a musical career for his daughter had to end, she became a teacher at the age of 13.
When Sigismond Thalberg visited Charleston, in 1857, he called upon Barbot, and was so delighted with her playing that he invited her to render with him a duo on two pianos at his concert.
In 1863, she married P. J. Barbot.
a merchant of Charleston, who died in 1887, leaving six children.
For years, she gave cantatas, oratorios and operas with the amateurs of the city.
In 1875, Barbot was selected as director of the Charleston Musical Association, a society of about 100 voices, with which she gave many important works.
She died December 17, 1919 in Charleston and was buried in that city's Saint Lawrence Cemetery.
